# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: directed-evolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Directed evolution has its origins in the 1960s with the evolution of RNA molecules in the "Spiegelman's Monster" experiment.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The concept was extended to protein evolution via evolution of bacteria under selection pressures that favoured the evolution of a single gene in its genome.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Early phage display techniques in the 1980s allowed targeting of mutations and selection to a single protein.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This enabled selection of enhanced binding proteins, but was not yet compatible with selection for catalytic activity of enzymes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Methods to evolve enzymes were developed in the 1990s and brought the technique to a wider scientific audience.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The field rapidly expanded with new methods for making libraries of gene variants and for screening their activity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The development of directed evolution methods was honored in 2018 with the awarding of the Nobel Prize in Chemistry to Frances Arnold for evolution of enzymes, and George Smith and Gregory Winter for phage display.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Directed evolution is a mimic of the natural evolution cycle in a laboratory setting.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Evolution requires three things to happen: variation between replicators, that the variation causes fitness differences upon which selection acts, and that this variation is heritable.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] In DE, a single gene is evolved by iterative rounds of mutagenesis, selection or screening, and amplification.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Rounds of these steps are typically repeated, using the best variant from one round as the template for the next to achieve stepwise improvements.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The likelihood of success in a directed evolution experiment is directly related to the total library size, as evaluating more mutants increases the chances of finding one with the desired properties.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The first step in performing a cycle of directed evolution is the generation of a library of variant genes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The sequence space for random sequence is vast (10130 possible sequences for a 100 amino acid protein) and extremely sparsely populated by functional proteins.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Neither experimental, nor natural evolution can ever get close to sampling so many sequences.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Of course, natural evolution samples variant sequences close to functional protein sequences and this is imitated in DE by mutagenising an already functional gene.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Some calculations suggest it is entirely feasible that for all practical (i.e. functional and structural) purposes, protein sequence space has been fully explored during the course of evolution of life on Earth.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The starting gene can be mutagenised by random point mutations (by chemical mutagens or error prone PCR) and insertions and deletions (by transposons).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Gene recombination can be mimicked by DNA shuffling of several sequences (usually of more than 70% sequence identity) to jump into regions of sequence space between the shuffled parent genes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Finally, specific regions of a gene can be systematically randomised for a more focused approach based on structure and function knowledge.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Depending on the method, the library generated will vary in the proportion of functional variants it contains.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Even if an organism is used to express the gene of interest, by mutagenising only that gene the rest of the organism's genome remains the same and can be ignored for the evolution experiment (to the extent of providing a constant genetic environment).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The majority of mutations are deleterious and so libraries of mutants tend to mostly have variants with reduced activity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Therefore, a high-throughput assay is vital for measuring activity to find the rare variants with beneficial mutations that improve the desired properties.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Two main categories of method exist for isolating functional variants.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] **Selection** systems directly couple protein function to survival of the gene, whereas **screening** systems individually assay each variant and allow a quantitative threshold to be set for sorting a variant or population of variants of a desired activity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Both selection and screening can be performed in living cells (*in vivo* evolution) or performed directly on the protein or RNA without any cells (*in vitro* evolution).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] During *in vivo* evolution, each cell (usually bacteria or yeast) is transformed with a plasmid containing a different member of the variant library.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] In this way, only the gene of interest differs between the cells, with all other genes being kept the same.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The cells express the protein either in their cytoplasm or surface where its function can be tested.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This format has the advantage of selecting for properties in a cellular environment, which is useful when the evolved protein or RNA is to be used in living organisms.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] When performed without cells, DE involves using *in vitro* transcription translation to produce proteins or RNA free in solution or compartmentalised in artificial microdroplets.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This method has the benefits of being more versatile in the selection conditions (e.g. temperature, solvent), and can express proteins that would be toxic to cells.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Furthermore, *in vitro* evolution experiments can generate far larger libraries (up to 1015) because the library DNA need not be inserted into cells (often a limiting step).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Selection for binding activity is conceptually simple.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The target molecule is immobilised on a solid support, a library of variant proteins is flowed over it, poor binders are washed away, and the remaining bound variants recovered to isolate their genes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Binding of an enzyme to immobilised covalent inhibitor has been also used as an attempt to isolate active catalysts.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This approach, however, only selects for single catalytic turnover and is not a good model of substrate binding or true substrate reactivity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] If an enzyme activity can be made necessary for cell survival, either by synthesizing a vital metabolite, or destroying a toxin, then cell survival is a function of enzyme activity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Such systems are generally only limited in throughput by the transformation efficiency of cells.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] They are also less expensive and labour-intensive than screening, however they are typically difficult to engineer, prone to artefacts and give no information on the range of activities present in the library.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] An alternative to selection is a screening system.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Each variant gene is individually expressed and assayed to quantitatively measure the activity (most often by a colourgenic or fluorogenic product).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The variants are then ranked and the experimenter decides which variants to use as templates for the next round of DE.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Even the most high throughput assays usually have lower coverage than selection methods but give the advantage of producing detailed information on each one of the screened variants.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This disaggregated data can also be used to characterise the distribution of activities in libraries which is not possible in simple selection systems.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Screening systems, therefore, have advantages when it comes to experimentally characterising adaptive evolution and fitness landscapes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] When functional proteins have been isolated, it is necessary that their genes are too, therefore a genotype–phenotype link is required.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This can be covalent, such as mRNA display where the mRNA gene is linked to the protein at the end of translation by puromycin.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Alternatively the protein and its gene can be co-localised by compartmentalisation in living cells or emulsion droplets.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The gene sequences isolated are then amplified by PCR or by transformed host bacteria.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Either the single best sequence, or a pool of sequences can be used as the template for the next round of mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The repeated cycles of Diversification-Selection-Amplification generate protein variants adapted to the applied selection pressures.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Rational design of a protein relies on an in-depth knowledge of the protein structure, as well as its catalytic mechanism.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Specific changes are then made by site-directed mutagenesis in an attempt to change the function of the protein.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] A drawback of this is that even when the structure and mechanism of action of the protein are well known, the change due to mutation is still difficult to predict.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Therefore, an advantage of DE is that there is no need to understand the mechanism of the desired activity or how mutations would affect it.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] A restriction of directed evolution is that a high-throughput assay is required in order to measure the effects of a large number of different random mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This can require extensive research and development before it can be used for directed evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Additionally, such assays are often highly specific to monitoring a particular activity and so are not transferable to new DE experiments.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Additionally, selecting for improvement in the assayed function simply generates improvements in the assayed function.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] To understand how these improvements are achieved, the properties of the evolving enzyme have to be measured.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Improvement of the assayed activity can be due to improvements in enzyme catalytic activity or enzyme concentration.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] There is also no guarantee that improvement on one substrate will improve activity on another.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This is particularly important when the desired activity cannot be directly screened or selected for and so a 'proxy' substrate is used.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] DE can lead to evolutionary specialisation to the proxy without improving the desired activity.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Consequently, choosing appropriate screening or selection conditions is vital for successful DE.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The speed of evolution in an experiment also poses a limitation on the utility of directed evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] For instance, evolution of a particular phenotype, while theoretically feasible, may occur on time-scales that are not practically feasible.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Recent theoretical approaches have aimed to overcome the limitation of speed through an application of counter-diabatic driving techniques from statistical physics, though this has yet to be implemented in a directed evolution experiment.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Combined, 'semi-rational' approaches are being investigated to address the limitations of both rational design and directed evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Beneficial mutations are rare, so large numbers of random mutants have to be screened to find improved variants.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] 'Focused libraries' concentrate on randomising regions thought to be richer in beneficial mutations for the mutagenesis step of DE.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] A focused library contains fewer variants than a traditional random mutagenesis library and so does not require such high-throughput screening.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Creating a focused library requires some knowledge of which residues in the structure to mutate.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] For example, knowledge of the active site of an enzyme may allow just the residues known to interact with the substrate to be randomised.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Alternatively, knowledge of which protein regions are variable in nature can guide mutagenesis in just those regions.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Directed evolution is frequently used for protein engineering as an alternative to rational design, but can also be used to investigate fundamental questions of enzyme evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The study of natural evolution is traditionally based on extant organisms and their genes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] However, research is fundamentally limited by the lack of fossils (and particularly the lack of ancient DNA sequences) and incomplete knowledge of ancient environmental conditions.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Directed evolution investigates evolution in a controlled system of genes for individual enzymes, ribozymes and replicators (similar to experimental evolution of eukaryotes, prokaryotes and viruses).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] DE allows control of selection pressure, mutation rate and environment (both the abiotic environment such as temperature, and the biotic environment, such as other genes in the organism).
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] Additionally, there is a complete record of all evolutionary intermediate genes.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] This allows for detailed measurements of evolutionary processes, for example epistasis, evolvability, adaptive constraint fitness landscapes, and neutral networks.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The natural amino acid composition of proteomes can be changed by global canonical amino acids substitutions with suitable noncanonical counterparts under the experimentally imposed selective pressure.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] For example, global proteome-wide substitutions of natural amino acids with fluorinated analogs have been attempted in *Escherichia coli* and *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] A complete tryptophan substitution with thienopyrrole-alanine in response to 20899 UGG codons in *Escherichia coli* was reported in 2015 by Budisa and Söll.
[src:directed-evolution/directed-evolution] The experimental evolution of microbial strains with a clear-cut accommodation of an additional amino acid is expected to be instrumental for widening the genetic code experimentally.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] DNA shuffling utilizes random recombination as opposed to site-directed mutagenesis in order to generate proteins with unique attributes or combinations of desirable characteristics encoded in the parent genes such as thermostability and high activity.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The potential for DNA shuffling to produce novel proteins is exemplified by the figure shown on the right which demonstrates the difference between point mutations, insertions and deletions, and DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Specifically, this figure shows the use of DNA shuffling on two parent genes which enables the generation of recombinant proteins that have a random combination of sequences from each parent gene.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] This is distinct from point mutations in which one nucleotide has been changed, inserted, or deleted and insertions or deletions where a sequence of nucleotides has been added or removed, respectively.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] As a result of the random recombination, DNA shuffling is able to produce proteins with new qualities or multiple advantageous features derived from the parent genes.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Stemmer published the first paper on DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Since the introduction of the technique, DNA shuffling has been applied to protein and small molecule pharmaceuticals, bioremediation, vaccines, gene therapy, and evolved viruses.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Other techniques which yield similar results to DNA shuffling include random chimeragenesis on transient templates (RACHITT), random printing in vitro recombination (RPR), and the staggered extension process (StEP).
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] DNA shuffling by molecular breeding was first reported in 1994 by Willem P.C.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] He started by fragmenting the β-lactamase gene that had been amplified with the polymerase chain reaction (PCR) by using DNase I, which randomly cleaves DNA.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] He then completed a modified PCR reaction where primers were not employed which resulted in the annealing of homologous fragments or fragments with similar sequences.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Finally, these fragments were amplified by PCR.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Stemmer reported that the use of DNA shuffling in combination with backcrossing resulted in the elimination of non-essential mutations and an increase in the production of the antibiotic cefotaxime.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] He also emphasized the potential for molecular evolution with DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Specifically, he indicated the technique could be used to modify proteins.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] DNA shuffling has since been applied to generate libraries of hybrid or chimeric genes and has inspired family shuffling which is defined as the use of related genes in DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Additionally, DNA shuffling has been applied to protein and small molecule pharmaceuticals, bioremediation, gene therapy, vaccines, and evolved viruses.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] First, DNase I is used to fragment a set of parent genes into segments of double stranded DNA ranging from 10-50 bp to more than 1 kbp.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] This is followed by a PCR without primers.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] In the PCR, DNA fragments with sufficiently overlapping sequences will anneal to each other and then be extended by DNA polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The PCR extension will not occur unless there are DNA sequences of high similarity.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The important factors influencing the sequences synthesized in DNA shuffling are the DNA polymerase, salt concentrations, and annealing temperature.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] For example, the use of Taq polymerase for amplification of a 1 kbp fragment in a PCR of 20 cycles results in 33% to 98% of the products containing one or more mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Multiple cycles of PCR extension can be used to amplify the fragments.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The addition of primers that are designed to be complementary to the ends of the extended fragments are added to further amplify the sequences with another PCR.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Primers may be chosen to have additional sequences added on to their 5' ends, such as sequences for restriction enzyme recognition sites which are needed for ligation into a cloning vector.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] It is possible to recombine portions of the parent genes to generate hybrids or chimeric forms with unique properties, hence the term DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The disadvantage of molecular breeding is the requirement for the similarity between the sequences, which has inspired the development of other procedures for DNA shuffling.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Restriction enzymes are employed to fragment the parent genes.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The fragments are then joined together through ligation which can be accomplished with DNA ligase.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] For example, if two parent genes have three restriction sites fourteen different full-length gene hybrids can be created.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The main difference between DNA shuffling with restriction enzymes and molecular breeding is molecular breeding relies on the homology of the sequences for the annealing of the strands and PCR for extension whereas by using restriction enzymes, fragment ends that can be ligated are created.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The main advantages of using restriction enzymes include control over the number of recombination events and lack of PCR amplification requirement.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The main disadvantage is the requirement of common restriction enzyme sites.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] In order to generate segments ranging from 10-50 bp to more than 1 kb, DNase I is utilized.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The ends of the fragments are made blunt by adding T4 DNA polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Blunting the fragments is important for combining the fragments as incompatible sticky-ends, or overhangs, prevent end joining.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Hairpins with a specific restriction site are then added to the mixture of fragments.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Next, T4 DNA ligase is employed to ligate the fragments to form extended sequences.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The ligation of the hairpins to the fragments limits the length of the extended sequences by preventing the addition of more fragments.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Finally, in order to remove the hairpin loops, a restriction enzyme is utilized.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Nonhomologous random recombination differs from molecular breeding as homology of the ligated sequences is not necessary which is an advantage.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] However**,** because this process recombines the fragments randomly it is probable that a large fraction of the recombined DNA sequences will not have the desired characteristics which is a disadvantage.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Since DNA shuffling enables the recombination of genes, protein activities can be enhanced.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] For example, DNA shuffling has been used to increase the potency of phage-displayed recombinant interferons on murine and human cells.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Additionally, the improvement of green fluorescent protein (GFP) was accomplished with DNA shuffling by molecular breeding as a 45-fold greater signal than the standard for whole cell fluorescence was obtained.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Furthermore, the synthesis of diverse genes can also result in the production of proteins with novel attributes.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Therefore, DNA shuffling has been used to develop proteins to detoxify chemicals.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] For example, the homologous recombination method of DNA shuffling by molecular breeding has been utilized to enhance the detoxification of atrazine and arsenate.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] DNA shuffling has also been used to improve the degradation of biological pollutants.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Specifically, a recombinant E. coli strain has been created with the use of DNA shuffling by molecular breeding for the bioremediation of trichloroethylene (TCE), a potential carcinogen, which is less susceptible to toxic epoxide intermediates.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The ability to select desirable recombinants with DNA shuffling has been used in combination with screening strategies to enhance vaccine candidates against infections with an emphasis on improving immunogenicity, vaccine production, stability, and cross-reactivity to multiple strains of pathogens.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Some vaccine candidates for Plasmodium falciparum, dengue virus, encephalitic alphaviruses (including: VEEV, WEEV, and EEEV), human immunodeficiency virus-1 (HIV-1), and hepatitis B virus (HBV) have been investigated.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The requirements for human gene therapies include high purity, high-titer, and stability.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] DNA shuffling allows for the fabrication of retroviral vectors with these attributes.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] For example, DNA shuffling with molecular breeding was applied to six ecotropic murine leukemia virus (MLV) strains which resulted in the compilation of an extensive library of recombinant retrovirus and the identification of multiple clones with increased stability.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Furthermore, the application of DNA shuffling by molecular breeding on multiple parent adeno-associated virus (AAV) vectors was employed to generate a library of ten million chimeras.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The advantageous attributes obtained include increased resistance to human intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) and the production of cell tropism in the novel viruses.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] While DNA shuffling has become a useful technique for random recombination, other methods including RACHITT, RPR, and StEP have also been developed for this purpose.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Below are some advantages and disadvantages of these other methods for recombination.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] In RACHITT, fragments of single stranded (ss) parent genes are annealed onto a ss template resulting in decreased mismatching which is an advantage.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Additionally, RACHIIT enables genes with low sequence similarity to be recombined.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] However, a major disadvantage is the preparation of the ss fragments of the parent genes and ss template.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] These random primers are annealed to template DNA and are then extended by the Klenow fragment.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Next, the templates are removed and the fragments are assembled by homology in a process similar to PCR.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] Some major benefits include the smaller requirement for parent genes due to the use of ss templates and increased sequence diversity by mispriming and misincorporation.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] One disadvantage of RPR is the preparation of the template.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] In StEP, brief cycles of primer annealing to a template and extension by polymerase are employed to generate full-length sequences.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The main advantages of StEP are the simplicity of the method and the lack of fragment purification.
[src:directed-evolution/dna-shuffling] The disadvantages of StEP include that it is time consuming and requires sequence homology.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] In molecular biology, **mutagenesis** is an important laboratory technique whereby DNA mutations are deliberately engineered to produce libraries of mutant genes, proteins, strains of bacteria, or other genetically modified organisms.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The various constituents of a gene, as well as its regulatory elements and its gene products, may be mutated so that the functioning of a genetic locus, process, or product can be examined in detail.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The mutation may produce mutant proteins with interesting properties or enhanced or novel functions that may be of commercial use.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Mutant strains may also be produced that have practical application or allow the molecular basis of a particular cell function to be investigated.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Many methods of mutagenesis exist today.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Initially, the kind of mutations artificially induced in the laboratory were entirely random using mechanisms such as UV irradiation.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Random mutagenesis cannot target specific regions or sequences of the genome; however, with the development of site-directed mutagenesis, more specific changes can be made, making it useful in situations that random mutagenesis is not.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Since 2013, development of the CRISPR/Cas9 technology, based on a prokaryotic viral defense system, has allowed for the editing or mutagenesis of a genome *in vivo*.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Other techniques of mutagenesis include combinatorial and insertional mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Mutagenesis that is not random can be used to clone DNA, investigate the effects of mutagens, and engineer proteins.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] It also has medical applications such as helping immunocompromised patients, research and treatment of diseases including HIV and cancers, and curing of diseases such as beta thalassemia.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Early approaches to mutagenesis relied on methods which produced entirely random mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] In such methods, cells or organisms are exposed to mutagens such as UV radiation or mutagenic chemicals, and mutants with desired characteristics are then selected.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Hermann Muller discovered in 1927 that X-rays can cause genetic mutations in fruit flies, and went on to use the mutants he created for his studies in genetics.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] For *Escherichia coli*, mutants may be selected first by exposure to UV radiation, then plated onto an agar medium.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The colonies formed are then replica-plated, one in a rich medium, another in a minimal medium, and mutants that have specific nutritional requirements can then be identified by their inability to grow in the minimal medium.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Similar procedures may be repeated with other types of cells and with different media for selection.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] A number of methods for generating random mutations in specific proteins were later developed to screen for mutants with interesting or improved properties.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] These methods may involve the use of doped nucleotides in oligonucleotide synthesis, or conducting a PCR reaction in conditions that enhance misincorporation of nucleotides (error-prone PCR), for example by reducing the fidelity of replication or using nucleotide analogues.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] A variation of this method for integrating non-biased mutations in a gene is sequence saturation mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] PCR products which contain mutation(s) are then cloned into an expression vector and the mutant proteins produced can then be characterised.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] In animal studies, alkylating agents such as *N*-ethyl-*N*-nitrosourea (ENU) have been used to generate mutant mice.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Ethyl methanesulfonate (EMS) is also often used to generate animal, plant, and virus mutants.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] In a European Union law (as 2001/18 directive), this kind of mutagenesis may be used to produce GMOs but the products are exempted from regulation: no labeling, no evaluation.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Prior to the development of site-directed mutagenesis techniques, all mutations made were random, and scientists had to use selection for the desired phenotype to find the desired mutation.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Random mutagenesis techniques have an advantage in terms of how many mutations can be produced; however, while random mutagenesis can produce a change in single nucleotides, it does not offer much control as to which nucleotide is being changed.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Many researchers therefore seek to introduce selected changes to DNA in a precise, site-specific manner.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Early attempts uses analogs of nucleotides and other chemicals were first used to generate localized point mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Such chemicals include aminopurine, which induces an AT to GC transition, while nitrosoguanidine, bisulfite, and N4-hydroxycytidine may induce a GC to AT transition.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] These techniques allow specific mutations to be engineered into a protein; however, they are not flexible with respect to the kinds of mutants generated, nor are they as specific as later methods of site-directed mutagenesis and therefore have some degree of randomness.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Other technologies such as cleavage of DNA at specific sites on the chromosome, addition of new nucleotides, and exchanging of base pairs it is now possible to decide where mutations can go.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Current techniques for site-specific mutation originates from the primer extension technique developed in 1978.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Such techniques commonly involve using pre-fabricated mutagenic oligonucleotides in a primer extension reaction with DNA polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] This methods allows for point mutation or deletion or insertion of small stretches of DNA at specific sites.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Advances in methodology have made such mutagenesis now a relatively simple and efficient process.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Newer and more efficient methods of site directed mutagenesis are being constantly developed.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] For example, a technique called "Seamless ligation cloning extract" (or SLiCE for short) allows for the cloning of certain sequences of DNA within the genome, and more than one DNA fragment can be inserted into the genome at once.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Site directed mutagenesis allows the effect of specific mutation to be investigated.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] There are numerous uses; for example, it has been used to determine how susceptible certain species were to chemicals that are often used In labs.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The experiment used site directed mutagenesis to mimic the expected mutations of the specific chemical.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The mutation resulted in a change in specific amino acids and the effects of this mutation were analyzed.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The site-directed approach may be done systematically in such techniques as alanine scanning mutagenesis, whereby residues are systematically mutated to alanine in order to identify residues important to the structure or function of a protein.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Another comprehensive approach is site saturation mutagenesis where one codon or a set of codons may be substituted with all possible amino acids at the specific positions.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Combinatorial mutagenesis is a site-directed protein engineering technique whereby multiple mutants of a protein can be simultaneously engineered based on analysis of the effects of additive individual mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] It provides a useful method to assess the combinatorial effect of a large number of mutations on protein function.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Large numbers of mutants may be screened for a particular characteristic by combinatorial analysis.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] In this technique, multiple positions or short sequences along a DNA strand may be exhaustively modified to obtain a comprehensive library of mutant proteins.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The rate of incidence of beneficial variants can be improved by different methods for constructing mutagenesis libraries.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] One approach to this technique is to extract and replace a portion of the DNA sequence with a library of sequences containing all possible combinations at the desired mutation site.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The content of the inserted segment can include sequences of structural significance, immunogenic property, or enzymatic function.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] A segment may also be inserted randomly into the gene in order to assess structural or functional significance of a particular part of a protein.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The insertion of one or more base pairs, resulting in DNA mutations, is also known as insertional mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Engineered mutations such as these can provide important information in cancer research, such as mechanistic insights into the development of the disease.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Retroviruses and transposons are the chief instrumental tools in insertional mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Retroviruses, such as the mouse mammary tumor virus and murine leukemia virus, can be used to identify genes involved in carcinogenesis and understand the biological pathways of specific cancers.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Transposons, chromosomal segments that can undergo transposition, can be designed and applied to insertional mutagenesis as an instrument for cancer gene discovery.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] These chromosomal segments allow insertional mutagenesis to be applied to virtually any tissue of choice while also allowing for more comprehensive, unbiased depth in DNA sequencing.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Researchers have found four mechanisms of insertional mutagenesis that can be used on humans. the first mechanism is called enhancer insertion.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Enhancers boost transcription of a particular gene by interacting with a promoter of that gene.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] This particular mechanism was first used to help severely immunocompromised patients in need of bone marrow.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Gammaretroviruses carrying enhancers were then inserted into patients.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The second mechanism is referred to as promoter insertion.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Promoters provide our cells with the specific sequences needed to begin translation.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Promoter insertion has helped researchers learn more about the HIV virus.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The third mechanism is gene inactivation.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] An example of gene inactivation is using insertional mutagenesis to insert a retrovirus that disrupts the genome of the T cell in leukemia patients and giving them a specific antigen called CAR allowing the T cells to target cancer cells.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The final mechanisms is referred to as mRNA 3' end substitution.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Human genes occasionally undergo point mutations causing beta-thalassemia, a condition which interrupts red blood cell function.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] To fix this problem the correct gene sequence for the red blood cells are introduced and a substitution is made.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Homologous recombination can be used to produce specific mutation in an organism.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Vector containing DNA sequence similar to the gene to be modified is introduced to the cell, and by a process of recombination replaces the target gene in the chromosome.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] This method can be used to introduce a mutation or knock out a gene, for example as used in the production of knockout mice.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] Since 2013, the development of CRISPR-Cas9 technology has allowed for the efficient introduction of different types of mutations into the genome of a wide variety of organisms.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] The method does not require a transposon insertion site, leaves no marker, and its efficiency and simplicity has made it the preferred method for genome editing.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] As the cost of DNA oligonucleotide synthesis falls, artificial synthesis of a complete gene is now a viable method for introducing mutations into a gene.
[src:directed-evolution/error-prone-pcr] This method allows for extensive mutation at multiple sites, including the complete redesign of the codon usage of a gene to optimise it for a particular organism.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In evolutionary biology, **fitness landscapes** or **adaptive landscapes** (types of evolutionary landscapes) are used to visualize the relationship between genotypes and reproductive success.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] It is assumed that every genotype has a well-defined replication rate (often referred to as fitness).
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] This fitness is the *height* of the landscape.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Genotypes which are similar are said to be *close* to each other, while those that are very different are *far* from each other.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The set of all possible genotypes, their degree of similarity, and their related fitness values is then called a fitness landscape.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The idea of studying evolution by visualizing the distribution of fitness values as a kind of landscape was first introduced by Sewall Wright in 1932.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In evolutionary optimization problems, fitness landscapes are evaluations of a fitness function for all candidate solutions (see below).
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In all fitness landscapes, height represents and is a visual metaphor for fitness.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] There are three distinct ways of characterizing the other dimensions, though in each case distance represents and is a metaphor for degree of dissimilarity.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Fitness landscapes are often conceived of as ranges of mountains.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] There exist local peaks (points from which all paths are downhill, i.e. to lower fitness) and valleys (regions from which many paths lead uphill).
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] A fitness landscape with many local peaks surrounded by deep valleys is called rugged.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] If all genotypes have the same replication rate, on the other hand, a fitness landscape is said to be flat.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] An evolving population typically climbs uphill in the fitness landscape, by a series of small genetic changes, until – in the infinite time limit – a local optimum is reached.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Note that a local optimum cannot always be found even in evolutionary time: if the local optimum can be found in a reasonable amount of time then the fitness landscape is called "easy" and if the time required is exponential then the fitness landscape is called "hard".
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Hard landscapes are characterized by the maze-like property by which an allele that was once beneficial becomes deleterious, forcing evolution to backtrack.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] However, the presence of the maze-like property in biophysically inspired fitness landscapes may not be sufficient to generate a hard landscape.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Wright visualized a genotype space as a hypercube.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] No continuous genotype "dimension" is defined.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Instead, a network of genotypes are connected via mutational paths.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Stuart Kauffman's NK model falls into this category of fitness landscape.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Newer network analysis techniques such as selection-weighted attraction graphing (SWAG) also use a dimensionless genotype space.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Wright's mathematical work described fitness as a function of allele frequencies.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Here, each dimension describes an allele frequency at a different gene, and goes between 0 and 1.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In the third kind of fitness landscape, each dimension represents a different phenotypic trait.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Under the assumptions of quantitative genetics, these phenotypic dimensions can be mapped onto genotypes.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] See the visualizations below for examples of phenotype to fitness landscapes.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Fitness seascapes extend the static fitness-landscape model by allowing the adaptive topography to shift through time or across changing environments.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The concept has also been formalized in statistical-physical models that analyse time-dependent selection gradients, adaptive fluxes, and the movement of peaks in a changing environment.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Fitness seascapes thus generalize traditional fitness landscapes by incorporating non-stationary selection, making them a useful framework for studying adaptation in fluctuating or clinically modulated environments.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Apart from the field of evolutionary biology, the concept of a fitness landscape has also gained importance in evolutionary optimization methods such as genetic algorithms or evolution strategies.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In evolutionary optimization, one tries to solve real-world problems (e.g., engineering or logistics problems) by imitating the dynamics of biological evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] For example, a delivery truck with a number of destination addresses can take a large variety of different routes, but only very few will result in a short driving time.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In order to use many common forms of evolutionary optimization, one has to define for every possible solution *s* to the problem of interest (i.e., every possible route in the case of the delivery truck) how 'good' it is.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] This is done by introducing a scalar-valued function *f(s)* (scalar valued means that *f(s)* is a simple number, such as 0.3, while *s* can be a more complicated object, for example a list of destination addresses in the case of the delivery truck), which is called the fitness function.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] A high *f(s)* implies that *s* is a good solution.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In the case of the delivery truck, *f(s)* could be the number of deliveries per hour on route *s*.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The best, or at least a very good, solution is then found in the following way: initially, a population of random solutions is created.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Then, the solutions are mutated and selected for those with higher fitness, until a satisfying solution has been found.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Even in cases where a fitness function is hard to define, the concept of a fitness landscape can be useful.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] For example, if fitness evaluation is by stochastic sampling, then sampling is from a (usually unknown) distribution at each point; nevertheless is can be useful to reason about the landscape formed by the expected fitness at each point.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] If fitness changes with time (dynamic optimisation) or with other species in the environment (co-evolution), it can still be useful to reason about the trajectories of the instantaneous fitness landscape.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] However, in some cases (for example, preference-based interactive evolutionary computation) the relevance is more limited, because there is no guarantee that human preferences are consistent with a single fitness assignment.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The concept of a scalar valued fitness function *f(s)* also corresponds to the concept of a potential or energy function in physics.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] The two concepts only differ in that physicists traditionally think in terms of minimizing the potential function, while biologists prefer the notion that fitness is being maximized.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Therefore, taking the inverse of a potential function turns it into a fitness function, and vice versa.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Since the human mind struggles to think in greater than three dimensions, 3D topologies can mislead when discussing highly multi-dimensional fitness landscapes.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] In particular it is not clear whether peaks in natural biological fitness landscapes are ever truly separated by fitness valleys in such multidimensional landscapes, or whether they are connected by vastly long neutral ridges.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Additionally, the fitness landscape is not static in time but dependent on the changing environment and evolution of other genes.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] It is hence more of a seascape, further affecting how separated adaptive peaks can actually be.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Additionally, it is relevant to take into account that a landscape is in general not an absolute but a relative function.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Finally, since it is common to use function as a proxy for fitness when discussing enzymes, any promiscuous activities exist as overlapping landscapes that together will determine the ultimate fitness of the organism, implying a gap between different coexisting relative landscapes.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] With these limitations in mind, fitness landscapes can still be an instructive way of thinking about evolution.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] It is fundamentally possible to measure (even if not to visualise) some of the parameters of landscape ruggedness and of peak number, height, separation, and clustering.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Simplified 3D landscapes can then be used relative to each other to visually represent the relevant features.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Additionally, fitness landscapes of small subsets of evolutionary pathways may be experimentally constructed and visualized, potentially revealing features such as fitness peaks and valleys.
[src:directed-evolution/fitness-landscape] Fitness landscapes of evolutionary pathways indicate the probable evolutionary steps and endpoints among sets of individual mutations.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Ribosome display begins with a native library of DNA sequences coding for polypeptides.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Each sequence is transcribed, and then translated *in vitro* into a polypeptide.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] However, the DNA library coding for a particular library of binding proteins is genetically fused to a spacer sequence lacking a stop codon before its end.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] The lack of a stop codon prevents release factors from binding and triggering the disassembly of the translational complex.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] So, this spacer sequence stays attached to the peptidyl tRNA and occupies the ribosomal tunnel, and thus allows the protein of interest to protrude out of the ribosome and fold.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] What results is a complex of mRNA, ribosome, and protein which can bind to surface-bound ligand.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] This complex is stabilized with the lowering of temperature and the addition of cations such as Mg2+.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] During the subsequent binding, or panning, stages, the complex is introduced to a surface-bound ligand.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] This can be accomplished in several ways, for example using an affinity chromatography column with a resin bed containing ligand, a 96-well plate with immobilized surface-bound ligand, or magnetic beads that have been coated with ligand.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] The complexes that bind well are immobilized.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Subsequent elution of the binders via high salt concentrations, chelating agents, or mobile ligands which complex with the binding motif of the protein allow dissociation of the mRNA.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] The mRNA can then be reverse transcribed back into cDNA, undergo mutagenesis, and iteratively fed into the process with greater selective pressure to isolate even better binders.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] At the same time, this method relies on generating large, concentrated pools of sequence diversity without gaps and keeping these sequences from degrading, hybridizing, and reacting with each other in ways that would create sequence-space gaps.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] It has a successful track record in the engineering of antibody and protein therapeutic leads and is still widely used in these areas.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Competing methods for protein evolution *in vitro* are phage display, yeast display, bacterial display, and mRNA display. peptides (Mattheakis, Bhatt and Dow) As it is performed entirely in vitro, there are two main advantages over other selection technologies.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] First, the diversity of the library is not limited by the transformation efficiency of bacterial cells, but only by the number of ribosomes and different mRNA molecules present in the test tube.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Second, random mutations can be introduced easily after each selection round, as no library must be transformed after any diversification step.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] This allows facile directed evolution of binding proteins over several generations.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] A prerequisite for the selection of proteins from libraries is the coupling of genotype (RNA, DNA) and phenotype (protein).
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] In ribosome display, this link is accomplished during in vitro translation by stabilizing the complex consisting of the ribosome, the mRNA and the nascent, correctly folded polypeptide.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] The ribosomal complexes are allowed to bind to surface-immobilized target.
[src:directed-evolution/ribosome-display] Whereas non-bound complexes are washed away, mRNA of the complexes displaying a binding polypeptide can be recovered, and thus, the genetic information of the binding polypeptides is available for analysis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] New techniques for achieving site-directed mutagenesis continue to be developed.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] For example, the development of CRISPR/Cas9 technologies, based on a prokaryotic viral defense system, has allowed for precisely targeted editing of the genome *in vivo*, which is sometimes considered a type of site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Early attempts at mutagenesis using radiation or chemical mutagens were not site-specific, instead generating random mutations in unpredictable locations.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Nucleic acid analogues and other chemicals were later used to generate localized point mutations; examples of such chemicals include aminopurine, nitrosoguanidine, and bisulfite.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Site-directed mutagenesis was first achieved in 1974 in the laboratory of Charles Weissmann using the nucleotide analogue N4-hydroxycytidine, which induces transition mutations of GC to AT.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] These methods of mutagenesis, however, are limited by the kinds of mutation they can achieve, and they are more likely to result in non-specific, off-target mutations than later site-directed mutagenesis methods.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] In 1971, Clyde Hutchison and Marshall Edgell showed that it is possible to produce mutants with small fragments of phage ΦX174 and restriction nucleases.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Hutchison later produced with his collaborator Michael Smith a more flexible approach to site-directed mutagenesis by using oligonucleotides in a primer extension method with DNA polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] For his part in the development of this process, Smith later shared the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in October 1993 with Kary B.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Mullis, who invented the polymerase chain reaction.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The basic procedure of site-directed mutagenesis requires the synthesis of a short DNA oligonucleotide primer.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This synthetic primer contains the desired mutation and is complementary to the DNA sequence around the mutation site so that it can hybridize with the DNA template.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The mutation may constitute one or more base substitutions (a point mutation), deletions, or insertions.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The single-stranded primer is then used as the starting point for the synthesis of a new DNA molecule by DNA polymerase, which copies the rest of the gene from the complementary template.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The newly synthesized molecule thus contains the mutated site, and is then introduced into a host cell in a plasmid vector and cloned.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Finally, DNA sequencing of the plasmid DNA purified from colonies grown from the transformed cells is used to check that they contain the desired mutation.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The original method using single-primer extension was inefficient due to a low yield of mutants.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This resulting mixture contains both the original unmutated template as well as the mutant strand, producing a mixed population of mutant and non-mutant progenies.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Furthermore, the template used is methylated while the mutant strand is unmethylated, and the mutants may be counter-selected due to the presence of a mismatch repair system that favors the methylated template DNA, resulting in fewer mutants.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Many approaches have since been developed to improve the efficiency of mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] A large number of techniques are now available to achieve site-directed mutagenesis, although most of them have rarely been used in laboratories since the early 2000s, as newer techniques have allowed for faster and easier ways of introducing site-specific mutations into genes.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] In 1985, Thomas Kunkel introduced a technique that reduces the need to select for the mutants.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The DNA fragment to be mutated is inserted into a phagemid such as M13mp18/19 and is then transformed into an *E. coli* strain deficient in two enzymes, dUTPase (*dut*) and uracil deglycosidase (*udg*).
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Both enzymes are part of a DNA repair pathway that protects the bacterial chromosome from mutations by the spontaneous deamination of dCTP to dUTP.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The dUTPase deficiency prevents the breakdown of dUTP, resulting in a high level of dUTP in the cell.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The uracil deglycosidase deficiency prevents the removal of uracil from newly synthesized DNA.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] As the double-mutant *E. coli* replicates the phage DNA, its enzymatic machinery may, therefore, misincorporate dUTP instead of dTTP, resulting in single-stranded DNA that contains some uracils (ssUDNA).
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The ssUDNA is extracted from the bacteriophage that is released into the medium, and then used as a template for mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] An oligonucleotide containing the desired mutation is used for primer extension.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The heteroduplex DNA that forms consists of one parental non-mutated strand containing dUTP and a mutated strand containing dTTP.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The DNA is then transformed into an *E. coli* strain carrying the wild-type *dut* and *udg* genes.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Here, the uracil-containing parental DNA strand is degraded, so that nearly all of the resulting DNA consists of the mutated strand.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Unlike other methods, cassette mutagenesis need not involve primer extension using DNA polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] In this method, a fragment of DNA is synthesized and then inserted into a plasmid.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] It involves cleavage by a restriction enzyme at restriction sites in the plasmid and the subsequent ligation into the plasmid of a pair of complementary oligonucleotides containing the mutation in the gene of interest.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Usually, the restriction enzymes that cut at the plasmid and the oligonucleotide are the same, permitting sticky ends of the plasmid and insert to ligate to one another.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This method can generate mutants at close to 100% efficiency, but is limited by the availability of suitable restriction sites flanking the site that is to be mutated.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The limitation of restriction sites in cassette mutagenesis may be overcome by using the polymerase chain reaction with oligonucleotide "primers", such that a larger fragment is generated, covering two convenient restriction sites.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The exponential amplification in PCR produces a fragment containing the desired mutation in sufficient quantities to be separated from the original, unmutated plasmid by gel electrophoresis, which may then be inserted into the original context using standard recombinant molecular biology techniques.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] There are many variations of the same technique.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The simplest method places the mutation site toward one of the ends of the fragment whereby one of two oligonucleotides used for generating the fragment contains the mutation.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This involves a single step of PCR, but still has the inherent problem of requiring a suitable restriction site near the mutation site unless a very long primer is used.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] These methods require multiple steps of PCR so that the final fragment to be ligated can contain the desired mutation.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The design process for generating a fragment with the desired mutation and relevant restriction sites can be cumbersome.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Software tools like SDM-Assist can simplify the process.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] For plasmid manipulations, other site-directed mutagenesis techniques have been supplanted largely by techniques that are highly efficient but relatively simple, easy to use, and commercially available as a kit.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] An example of these techniques is the "Quikchange" method, wherein a pair of complementary mutagenic primers are used to amplify the entire plasmid in a thermocycling reaction using a high-fidelity non-strand-displacing DNA polymerase such as *Pfu* polymerase.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The reaction generates a nicked, circular DNA molecule.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The template DNA must be eliminated by enzymatic digestion with a restriction enzyme such as *Dpn*I, which is specific for methylated DNA.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] All DNA replicated in the cells of most *Escherichia coli* strains is methylated; the template plasmid that is biosynthesized in *E. coli* will, therefore, be digested, while the mutated plasmid, which is generated *in vitro* and is therefore unmethylated, will be left undigested.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] In this case the amplification is linear, and it is therefore inaccurate to describe the procedure as PCR, since there is no chain reaction.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] However, if the primers are designed to bind in an offset manner such that the mutagenesis site is close to the 5' ends of both primers, the 3' regions of the primers can bind also to the amplified products and thus exponential product formation is observed.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The name "Quikchange" originates from the registered trademark "QuikChange mutagenesis" of Stratagene, now Agilent Technologies, for site-directed mutagenesis kits.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] The method was developed by scientists working at Stratagene.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Note that *Pfu* polymerase can become strand-displacing at higher extension temperatures (≥70 °C) which can result in the failure of the experiment, therefore the extension reaction should be performed at the recommended temperature of 68 °C.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] In some applications, this method has been observed to lead to insertion of multiple copies of primers.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] A variation of this method, called SPRINP, prevents these artifacts and has been used in different types of site-directed mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Other techniques such as scanning mutagenesis of oligo-directed targets (SMOOT) can semi-randomly combine mutagenic oligonucleotides in plasmid mutagenesis.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This technique can create plasmid mutagenesis libraries ranging from single mutations to comprehensive codon mutagenesis across an entire gene.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Since 2013, the development of CRISPR/Cas9 genome editing technologies has allowed for the efficient introduction of various mutations into genomic DNA in a wide variety of organisms.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] Site-directed mutagenesis is used to generate mutations that may produce a rationally designed protein that has improved or special properties (i.e. protein engineering).
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] As the cost of DNA oligonucleotide synthesis falls, artificial synthesis of a complete gene *de novo* is now a viable method for introducing mutations into genes.
[src:directed-evolution/site-directed-mutagenesis] This method allows for extensive mutagenesis over multiple sites, including the complete redesign of the codon usage of the gene to optimise it for expression in a particular organism.
